5. FUNCTIONAL COMPONENTS
A. Provider Abstraction
⦁	Uses a service layer for Gemini API with flexible request/response handling.
⦁	Configurable parameters (model, temperature, timeout).
⦁	Easily extensible to other AI providers in future.

B. Context & Memory

⦁	Session-based history management using MongoDB.
⦁	Auto-summarization for long conversations to save tokens.
⦁	Functions for clearing, resetting, or attaching system prompts dynamically.

C. Streaming APIs

⦁	/chat endpoint created with Server-Sent Events (SSE).
⦁	Streams partial responses token by token for smoother experience.
⦁	Heartbeat and backpressure handling for connection stability.

D. React Chat UI

⦁	Built with React.js and includes:
⦁	Typing indicators and live streaming messages.
⦁	Retry and error handling options.
⦁	Timestamps and grouped message display.
⦁	Context controls (clear/summarize/reset).

E. Persistence

⦁	MongoDB collections for users, sessions, and chat logs.
⦁	TTL (Time-To-Live) for inactive sessions.
⦁	Option to export or download full conversations.

F. Safety & Guardrails

⦁	Prompt injection filtering and input sanitization.
⦁	Rate limiting per user session.
⦁	Environment-based secret management.

G. Authentication & Security

⦁	JWT-based user authentication.
⦁	CORS and CSRF protection enabled.
⦁	Secure cookie-based sessions or headers.

H. Observability & Monitoring

⦁	Metrics for latency, API errors, and token usage.
⦁	Logging with correlation IDs for debugging.
⦁	Cost tracking for per-user AI usage.

I. Testing

⦁	Mock Gemini provider for local testing.
⦁	Unit and integration tests for backend routes.
⦁	E2E (End-to-End) testing of conversation flow and persistence.

J. DevOps & Deployment

⦁	Docker Compose setup for easy deployment.
⦁	Environment-driven configurations for dev/test/prod.
⦁	Seed scripts for demo sessions and testing data.

